?! The key move of the controversial Latvian Gambit. Very rarely seen at high levels Black gives up a pawn (and usually much more) for a lead in space and development.
This is the main line which continues with 3...Qf6 (or 3...Nf6?!) and then either 4.d4 d6 5.Nc4 fxe4 or 4.Nc4 fxe4 5.Nc3 Qg6 6.d3.

?! This unusual variation leads to especially sharp lines as Black offers White a free Rook with 4.Qh5+ g6 5.Nxg6 Nf6 6.Qh3 hxg6 7.Qxh8 Qe7 hoping his positional compensation will be enough to deal with White's significant material lead.
This is not actually bad but it is probably the best-case scenario for Black as he gets to free up his LSB and the d-file without an enormous material sacrifice.

?! White is playing extremely aggressively but the e-pawn was in no real danger (...fxe4 isolates Black's pawn far from any support and will be won back easily) and White needs to develop in order to compete with what is about to become a very active Black position.
With no Knight and d4 blocked White doesn't have a comfortable way to dislodge this Queen.
This is the only way to protect the pawn until White can find time for f4 but it does the LSB no favors.
Black blockades the troublesome e-pawn and puts another piece between his King and the WQ.
Kicking the Queen but hampering White's development further.

!? Black allows his Queen to be somewhat marginalized but threatens White's b-pawn tying the WQ to its defense should the Bishop get out after White's d4. With only a couple pieces in play Black is making it exceedingly uncomfortable for White to complete his development.
Reinforcing the e-pawn though this seems susceptible to attack from ...c5.
White is still far behind in development and Black's pieces are looking hungrily at the WK--which is still at least three moves from castling.

?! White develops while trying to gain some tempo but Black has an easy response. What's worse this move ties the Queen to the defense of b2 and prevents White from playing an immediate Nd2 as a result.
I don't like this choice by White to trade off his only active piece. Perhaps 10.Be3 would be better threatening 11.d5.
Black is almost fully developed while only White's Queen is off her starting square--and she's not looking great either.
? White tries to loosen up his position a bit but it would have been better to simply bite the bullet and take the time to develop with 11.Qc2 followed by Bd3 and Nd2 as now Black can counter with...
! This sham sacrifice wins the pawn and gives Black undisputed control of the d-file. If 12.cxd4? Qxd4 and Black wins back his Rook with interest.
Now White can take the Rook but his queenside pawns and e-pawn are looking very weak.

?! I still don't know how to feel about this move. Black continues to apply pressure to White's cramped position and prevents f4 for the moment but he gives up the d-file and allows White to develop his Bishop with tempo.
Not 13...Bd5? (thinking to invade h1 and deny White's castle) because of 14.f3! simultaneously blocking the threat and winning the Rook.

?! Shoring up the advanced e-pawn yet again and locking Black's Rook out of the center. This does completely shatter any safety that was to be had in the White kingside though as Black can reach the h1-a8 diagonal first and now also controls all of g1-a7 as well. I think 14.Bg2 was better here.
Black seizes the diagonal for his Bishop. The tempting 14...g5?? (trying to undermine e5 yet again) loses badly to 15.Bh3.

?! Black's Rook is in a precarious spot with only one retreat square but it's safe for now and with both Rooks on the kingside he plans to break through White's pawns and get all his pieces into the attack before the King can escape the center.
Finally the Bishop gets out of the corner. After the Rook moves this Bishop will actually be of some use pinning Black's f-pawn.
White unpins his Knight and threatens Nd4 winning the f-pawn.
Forcing White to deal with his weak c3 pawn before anything else happens and provoking the natural response...
White kicks the powerfully-centralized Bishop though it won't go far...
! Clearing the WQ away from her defense of e4.
?! This is surprising. White wants to keep his Knight available for kingside maneuvers but putting his King on the open d-file is dangerous at best.
With the WQ gone Black's Bishop is now free to occupy this powerful location.

Another surprise though it's clear why White wants to trade off the Black Bishop. He leaves his King dangerously exposed though. I expected 21.Rae1 or maybe 21.Ke3 (thinking to work his way over to g1).

! Black has decided that 21...Rd8+ doesn't offer enough promise as the WK can easily flee to his kingside and hide amongst his pieces there. Instead Black tries to disrupt the White position and get an advantage for the endgame--now if White wants to eliminate the Black Bishop he'll let the Rooks in to wreak havoc on his kingside (22.Nxe4 hxg3 23.hxg3 Rxh3 and now the Knight must retreat allowing 24...Rhxg3).
White seeks to eliminate the pesky Bishop once and for all but Black's aggressive Rooks will be too strong for White's passive ones especially the Rf1 blocking the WB's escape route.

Black forges ahead with his kingside break. White has several options here none of them particularly pleasant. For instance 23.hxg3 Rxg5! 24. fxg5 (24.Bxf5+ Rxf5 25.Rxe4 Rh2+ 26.Re2 Rxe2+ 27.Kxe2 c5 gives Black a clearly won endgame) ...Rxh3 and Black's powerful Bishop is unassailable on e4 while the Knight and King clean up White's pawns. Alternately White could try 23.Nxe4 g2! 24.Bxg2 (24.Rg1 is met with ...Rxh3 25.Nf2 Rxh2) ...Rxg2+ 25.Nf2 Rhxh2 26.Re2 and White's pieces are hopelessly passive tied down to defending each other while the Black Knight and King and again free to roam the board.
! This Rook "sacrifices" itself for the second time. Black has too many threats to counter at once. He'll get at least two minor pieces and a pawn for his Rook if White takes it.
?! White counters by removing the powerful light-square Bishop but now he'll be down a Knight as the endgame approaches.
Black cleans up the Bishop and unpins his f-pawn while threatening to win g3 as well.
? White chooses to avoid more trades and save his Rook but trying to defend the g-pawn is a futile gesture. Better may have been 25.Rd4 trying for some counterplay on the d-file.
Black removes his own Rook from danger gains a pawn and now threatens to win the Re3 as well as the a2 pawn.
If White wanted to exchange Rooks it would have been more accurate to play 25.fxg5 fxe4 26.Ke3 Rxg3+ 27.Kxe4 where at least White has a good centralized position for his King.
Allowing White to interpose his Rook after ...Rg2+ though trading off more material isn't going to help him much.
With almost no pieces remaining on the board the Black King finally mobilizes to attempt to escort a pawn through the White camp.
White doesn't fall for the temptation of 30.Kg3 thinking to win a kingside pawn as that loses to 30...b5 31.Kf3 a5 32.Ke3 Ng6 33.c5 Ke6 etc.

Black gets his King in the most centralized location available ready to push to d5 whenever the opportunity presents itself. If now 31.Kd4 Black can play ...b6! and then White must mark time while the Black Knight relocates to d7: 32.a3 Ng6 33.Ke3 Nf8 34.Kd4 Nd7 35.Ke3 g5! 36.fxg5 Nxe5 37.Kf4 Ng6+ 38.Kg3 Ke5 and soon Black will win the g-pawn or simply push through on the queenside.
White keeps his King close by f4 but it won't do him much good. Black has too much material to throw at his problems.
There are few other choices.

! White has no resources left. 33.fxg5 loses the e-pawn then the g-pawn in due course. No queenside pushes are possible; Black simply has too many pawns there for White to break through. Avoiding capture of the f-pawn is no better anyway as ...Ng6 forces the issue soon enough.
Hoping for 33...bxa5 34.bxa5 and then maybe Black will blunder and allow the KW in through d5-c5.
White's queenside pawns pose no threat at all. Black can simply force the creation of a passed pawn on the kingside then march to victory on whichever flank the WK doesn't defend.
White chooses to go kingside hoping to defend his g-pawn and maybe drive the Knight away allowing a promotion if Black missteps.
But now Black will have a passed a-pawn as well and the WK cannot hope to defend both sides of the board.

0-1. White has no way to stop both the a- and f-pawns and he resigns. Many thanks to luker67 for this excellent game! Comments on the analysis or on the game itself are much appreciated. If you leave a rating please also comment letting me know what I did well or need to improve! Thanks for reading!
?! The key move of the controversial Latvian Gambit. Very rarely seen at high levels Black gives up a pawn (and usually much more) for a lead in space and development.
This is a less common line looking somewhat like a King's Gambit with the colors reversed. I don't think it generally fares as well as 3.Nxe5.
Black kicks the White Knight and aggressively establishes some space on the center. Whether he'll be able to hold it or not is another matter.
Standard is 4.Ne5 Nf6 5.Be2 but this is playable as well.
Threatening the Knight and developing the Queen to a surprisingly safe effective location. Black intends to make the very most of his half-open f-file.

I can't find any literature for this move. I think 5.Qh5+ is probably stronger (5...g6 6.fxg6 and now if 6...Qxg6 7.Qe5+ wins the Rook so 6...Qxd4 7.g7+ Ke7 and White promotes on move 8 winning material and stymieing the potential Black offensive.

? This seems logical but I think it's actually too defensive-minded. It's intended to release Black's other Bishop but I think advancing the d-pawn can wait while Black runs the White Knight out of town with 5...c5 6.Nb5 Qc6 7.Qh5+ Kd8. Now Black can play ...d5 and ...c4 at his leisure driving the Knight almost off the board altogether while securing the whole center for himself and preventing White from developing either of his Bishops.
White prepares to win a pawn.
6...Kd8 is probably better here. The text sacrifices quite a bit of material for open lines--much riskier but certainly in the spirit of the Latvian.
If 7...Qxg6? 8.Qe5+ wins the Rook and probably the game.
Black sacrifices another pawn in exchange for developing with tempo.
And another (b7) ...
Note that White couldn't win the Black Rook immediately with 10.Qxb7 because of ...Qe5+ 11.Be2 Be4. Now however Qxb7 followed by Qxa8 is a threat.
?! Black now dumps yet another pawn as well as his queenside Rook. White has nothing developed but his Queen but Black is running out of pieces altogether.
White decides his three-pawn lead should be sufficient for now and declines the Rook that Black was offering in favor of keeping his Queen nearby.

Black's Knight blocks the vulnerable b-pawn and develops toward the center. With this move Black also prepares to castle long getting his King to safety and bringing his other Rook into play. Another good-looking option was 11...Bh6 making White's developmental choices even more nightmarish by pinning his d-pawn.

White prepares his own castle and momentarily pressures the Nc6. I think c4 might have been a stronger place to develop this Bishop in order to prevent a Black Knight from coming to d5 after Black castles.

All of Black's pieces are now in the game. His DSB needs a better square and h6 is still tempting (pinning the d-pawn) but Black also wants to leave the h-file open for pressure against White's upcoming castle.
White gains some much-needed play for his own QB and QN. He has the makings of a dangerous attack against the Black queenside.
?! This sacrifice doesn't seem sound at all to me but it slims down White's queenside pawns and gives Black a big lead in space at the cost of half-opening the c-file for a White Rook.
Black now has plenty of space and uncontested control of the d-file.

? The WK skedaddles which is pretty reasonable. However this move allows the beautiful and deadly Black Queen to eliminate a critical White piece from the board. Black didn't have any immediate threats; simple queenside development with 15.Nc3 would have been a better choice.
! Black threatens mate on h2 leaving White no time to get his LSB out of danger.
This is a powerful dangerous diagonal for White's QB to occupy. There are a lot of pieces pointed at the BK.
Driving the BQ away and offering the pawn on b2-- White's position is very strong after 17...Qxb2 18. Rab1 Qxa2 19.Qxb7+ Kd7 20.Rfd1+ Ke8 21.Rxd8+ Kxd8 22.Qxc7+ Ke8 23.Rb8+ Kf7 24.Nb5.
Black doesn't take the bait instead positioning his Queen where she can support d4 and prevent the White Knight from charging up to b5 or c4.
White completes his development and bears down on c7.
The Knight finally gets off the a3-f8 diagonal and puts itself between White's attack and the BK preparing to jump into action with a much more powerful post on d4.

?! I'm not sure about this move. Black's pieces are somewhat disjointed and cannot defend both the Rook and the f-pawn in one move but by pulling his Bishop off the h2-b8 diagonal White relieves some of the pressure on the BK.
! Black's Knight leaps to a very strong centralized position defending the f-pawn and gaining time to get the Rook out of the way as well.
Basically forced. Somewhere to keep pressure on the Black queenside would be preferable but 20.Qg3 and 20.Qf4 both lose immediately to ...Ne2+!
Black can now casually lift his Rook out of danger threatening to swing over to the Kingside for a devastating attack.
!? White threatens the dangerous Rh8 but this attack is easily-parried and White is starting to lose sight of his formerly-strong attack on the Black King.

?! Black eagerly offers a trade for the piece that can best defend White's kingside. If now 22.Bxg7 Rxg7 Black has dangerous-looking attack down his half-open kingside files but the Nd4's position becomes fairly tenuous and White may have a terrific attack through the center.
No attempt to maintain the Knight on d4 is feasible because of 24.Rc4.
Threatening f5 as well as a mating battery down the d-file should the Black pieces stop defending d7 and d8.
Black struggles to keep his counterplay alive threatening to clean up some White pawns with tempo or otherwise tempt White into weakening his kingside fortress.

This defends against 25...Qxh2+ 26.Kf1 Qxg2+ but now White needs to keep a careful eye on his weak h3-pawn as it is only defended by the Queen and allowing a Black Rook to open the h-file would be devastating.

! Black's Knight returns to the center with a multitude of threats. The primary danger is that the threat on the WQ leaves her with very few locations to retreat to from which she can still defend h3. The Queen is also the only defender of f3 where the Knight is looking to deliver a nasty check so 26.Qd2 and Qd4 (thinking to trade off the powerful BQ) are impossible.

?? Overly concerned about the pin and various checking possibilities for Black White completely forgets about the immediate threat to his Queen. Best was probably 26.Qe3 Nf3+ 27.Kf1 Nh2+ 28.Ke2 Qxe3+ 29.Kxe3 Rxg2 where White will be a pawn down but with decent positional compensation.
? Not that it matters but White certainly can't afford to drop a Rook as well.

0-1. White's position is completely hopeless and he resigns. Thanks very much to speediecees for a great game and thank you dear reader for stopping by to check out this annotation. Any comments on the analysis or the game itself are much appreciated and if you leave a low rating please let me know what I can do to improve! Thanks for reading!
1...Nf6. I am unfamiliar with this opening. I have no idea why I played this.
4...d6 This Blocks off my Bishop but helps guard the e-pawn. It also lets out my Light Squared Bishop.
Both of My Bishops stare into the corner. Was Kingside the best way to Castle?
Pinning the pesky defending Knight.
Breaking the pin.
Lining up on diagonal and getting Black closer to Castling Queenside.
Forcing me to make a choice: take or retreat.
!? But take *what* is the real question! This move rips open White's King's cover.
!! Until this move White had been cramped with no hope of defense or counterplay. Now White's Bishop and Queen are released and spell trouble for Black.
Nd7 would be better.
Now I must move my King losing Castling possibility.
! Gets rid of my second attacker. Black's attack fizzles after the trade.
But Black doesn't want to trade -- he wants to give away a Rook and a Pawn.
! This cuts off the Bishop from the corner and threatens mate.
Believe it or not until this move Black had planned move 16.
?? Further blocking the Bishop but losing the Queen.
The rest of the game doesn't need annotation.
And here it is. An attack on the stronghold proved disastrous. Please leave comments and thanks for reading!
2....d5. The French Defense Reversed Philidor Variation. I'm not to familiar with this line but I don't think that I like it.
3.Qf3? This move is strange. I think that White should develop.
3....Nc6 Develops keeping tabs on e5 and d4.
4.Nh3? White should have probably played 4.Ne2 then fianchettoed his Light Squared Bishop since it has little future in the French center.
4....b6 I prepare for a fianchetto. This also allows Bc5 aligning the Bishops.
5.Ng5. Ahh so that's what he was getting at. No White should develop instead of attacking. Two pieces is hardly a battle-ready force.
5...Nf6. This develops and blocks the mate threat on f6.
6.c3. Preparing a d4 pawn push which would be follows by d4 e5 and my Dark Squared Bishop would be obsolete.
6....g6. This allows me to get my Dark Squared Bishop to a more useful location than his dying future on the a3-f8 diagonal.
7.d4. The aforementioned pawn push.
7....Bh6. This pins the Knight to the Bishop on c1.
8.e5. Now White controls the dark squares. And here is my first miscalculation.
8....Bxg5?? This miscalculation allows Black to win a minor piece.
9....O-O. I cannot move the Knight because of the pin and I had to castle to avoid losing even more material.
10....Qe8. Now everything goes downhill.
11.Qh3. This prepares for 12.Qh6 then mate is unavoidable.
11....h5. Only option.
12.Qe3. White is relentless. 13.Qh6 is unavoidable mate.
12....Kh7. Once again the only defense.
13.Be2. Probably preparing for a sac on h5 to rip away my defense.

13....Na5?? This is a huge blunder! I don't know what I was thinking. 13....Ne2 is obviously the correct move here. From e2 the Knight can move to f5 where it controls the h4 h6 g3 g7 e3 e7 and d6 squares. If White trades on e7 that removes a vital attacker from White's attack.
14.Qd3. This pins the g6 pawn and allows 15.Bxh5.
15...Qf8. Now that I have two defenders in the corner I will try to hang on with everything I have.
16....Qh6. Kicking the Bishop.
17....Rxg6?? The second miscalculation. I should have taken with the Queen or pawn.
18.Nb5. Plans to take on c7 it appears.
20.Nd6. Attacking the helpless f-pawn.
20....Kg8. Defending and releasing the pin.
21....Nb7. I try to trade Knights. I think that this is better than 21...Bb7. Once the Knight takes the Bishop retakes then I can move the d-pawn and my Bishop will stare down g2.
22.Nxc8. But White has other plans.
24.Qxa7. I thought this was the end of what his Queen would do. How wrong I was.
24....Qh3. This threatens mate but I overlooked HIS mate threat.
25.Qb8. I could resign here on account of unavoidable mate but I decided to draw it out as long as possible.
27....Kh7. The only move.

28.Qh8#

My opponent played well in this game and I played terribly. I overlooked miscalculated blundered and overall failed in the middle-late game. 

Thank you for reading! Please leave comments!
This is the Vienna Game an unusual opening that easily transposes into the Four Knights Game.
This is the Falkbeer variation.
As I have mentioned it is very easy to transpose into the Four Knights.
Worrying about 4...Nxe4? No problem Black gives me a chance to fend the move off.
Of course.
Black should simply Castle right now.
? It is horrible to lose material in the development phase of the Four Knights. Black instead of Castling gave me a free pawn.
Black has options. He can take my Knight and lose more material or he can defend his Knight. There is perhaps one more option and that will be covered below.
That one option is obviously Castling. Despite the fact that it loses more material it prevents the Kingside disaster that I do in this game.
It all starts with this move winning yet another free pawn.
This move isn't bad yet but I prefer 7...Kf8 with the problematic 8.Bxg6! to deal with.
This isn't very very bad for Black yet but it is very bad for him.
THIS is the bad move although no matter what Black does he loses. 8...Nf6 is met by 9.Qf3.
I am not missing out on taking the Queen.
Black has two options.
10...Kc6 11.Bd5#! That's why Black played this move.
I cannot save the Bishop unless I retreat it but in exchange this move offers 12.g4.
What other choice does Black have?
12.g4 was better but this move is still okay. 12.g4 Ng7 13.Nd5+ Kf8 14.Ne5 wins.
Here 13.Ne5 is a good idea.
Wastes the opportunity a little bit.
The only place for the Knight unless it wants to get taken.
The object is to bring every piece into the heart of the action.
Although mate isn't possible yet 15.Qxf7 wins six points for free.
Actually I have an idea for checkmate.
16.Nf6 followed by Qxg7 (if possible) should be able to win.
Instead I take no time to think and play this move.
I see what Black is doing. 17.Rf1 works.
All I need to do is be rid of the Rook on f8. This is achieved by chasing the King away from the Rook. Then again I also have to realize that the Bishop is also something I need to get rid of.
Now the King has to block the Bishop from protecting the Rook
Can you spot the move that wins a Rook?
! Since the King is pushed to take the Knight I can take the Rook. Note that if 19.Kf8 I still win the Rook.
Black play the expected move.
Warning that free Knight loses a free Bishop.
I guess Black didn't care for the Warning. The plan now is to help the Kingside pawns promote.
That is after I take the Bishop.
White's position is dangerous.
Black's going to get nothing done either way.
A simple method now is to eliminate the g6 and h7 pawns.
Making sure that my Rook gets into the Game.
I don't think that Black is trying in these next moves.
Step 1 of 4: promote the g-pawn.
What if Black did 28...d6 instead?
It is impossible to stop the Pawn from promoting.
Black's Bishop hops to this square in fear.

Finally Black resigns. Here's what the game could possibly look like: 30...Bc6 31.g8=Q Kb7 32.Ra6 Bb5 33.c4 Ka6 34.cxb5+ Kxb5 35.Qxd7+ and a mate in four at the most. Like Steintz explained a premature attack usually loses and this is one of those cases.feel free to editwhat the game could possibly look like because I may be missing better moves. When you have a chance to play a good move play before it's too late. A good move can become a horrible move in one turn if you don't play it.

Here's another exciting game in the Latvian Gambit this time the Svedenborg Variation characterized by 3.Bc4 and 4...d5 where White has a stronger-than-usual attack at the very beginning and despite the line being heavily analyzed the position is very sharp and frequently unclear. This game features a king hunt and a very strong attack and showcases what happens in this opening when Black has trouble getting his light-square Bishop into play.
?! The key move of the Latvian Gambit. Black gives up a pawn (and usually more) inviting White to trash the Black kingside in exchange for open files and a potential lead in development.
This is a particularly aggressive line for White to take. Like most of the other lines in the Latvian besides 3. Nxe5 this move's merit has been heavily disputed (and extensively analyzed).
Kicking the Knight inviting it to e5 for a threat on f7.
White accepts the generous offer threatening a fork on f7. Black doesn't seem to have any compensation for his risky opening as yet.
The more common line is 4...Qg5 5. d4 Qxg2 6. Qh5+ g6 7. Bf7+ Kd8 8. Bxg6 Qxh1+ 9. Ke2 Qxc1 10. Nf7+ but I think 4...d5 is stronger for Black.
6...hxg6 is a playable but less common alternative.
I can't find any literature for this move. More standard is 7. Qe5+ Be7 8. Bb5+ c6 9. Nxe7 Qxe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. Be2 and White is a pawn up but will lag considerably in development.
Unpinning the h-pawn but more importantly moving the Rook to the half-open g-file.
This is probably the best play here as White gobbles more material before his own pieces begin falling.

?! Black continues to postpone taking White pieces opting for a much more aggressive stance and in fact driving the White Queen forward to a defense of the f8 Knight. 8...Rxg2 is probably reasonable here as well and perhaps better as it leaves g4 open for the Black Knight.
White defends f8 but he no longer pins the Black Knight to the Queen allowing ...Rxg2 followed by ...Ng4 threatening a dangerous attack focused at f2.

?! Black is planning 10. Nxh7 Ng4 11. Qf4 Rxf2 12. Qxf2 Nxf2 13. Kxf2 Qh4+ winning back some material and drawing the WK into the open or if White is feeling less cooperative a few variations on a king hunt are possible with White chasing the BK to his queenside but unable to quite finish him off (for example 11. Qg6+ Ke7 12. Qg7+ Kd6 13. Qf8+ Qxf8 14. Nxf8 dxc4 or 14...Bf5 and Black has decent compensation for his material).

! Piling pressure on the indefensible d-pawn. 13...dxc4 would be ill-advised as it exposes Black to 14. Qxc4+ Kd6 or 14...Kd7 and White can chase the BK back across the board and trap him in the corner with his Queen and Knights.

The only way Black is getting out of this is if he gets some more pieces available for combat. With this move Black invites 14. Bb5+ Kd6 15. Qxd5+ Ke7 hoping to get his Bishop into play with tempo as soon as he gets a spare move and then allowing his Queen and Rook to enter the fight and return some pressure against the White King.

Not quite as strong as 14.Bb5+ I think but certainly still good. White seeks to corner Black's King using his Knight Bishop and a-pawn (eg 14...Kb6 15.a4 Rxf2 16.Qg6+ Ka5 17.b4+ Kxb4 18.Rb1+ Kc5 19.Rb5+ Kd4 20.Qxe4#).
This blocks b2-b4 making a5 a "safe" hiding place and opens space for the Black King on a6 in the event of 16.a5+.
White continues to press the assault making Black choose between claustrophobia on a6 and exposure on c5.
This is much safer than 16...Kc5 in my opinion. The BK may have to retreat all the way to b8 but at least he'll be safe there.
Threatening Qc4+ and mate to follow.
?? Black badly underestimates White's attacking chances here and pays the price swiftly. Much better for Black was 17...Qd4 shutting the WQ off from c4 and legitimizing his own attack.

1-0. That's all there is! The early development of the White light-square Bishop and Black's inability to get his pieces mobilized (coupled with a few questionable moves) prevented the aggressive counterplay Black so desperately needs in this opening leading to a painful demise for the harried Black King. Many thanks to invinlee85 for the game! Comments on the analysis or the game itself are much appreciated and if you leave a low rating please comment to tell me what I can improve! Thanks for reading!

This is one of the longest blitz games I've played with both of us getting right down to the wire on our timers. A big pawn block develops in the center and some slow positional play develops with two Bishops facing off against a Bishop and a Knight. I open with the English and the bind I set up on d5 leads to the central pawn structure the last fifty moves of the game revolve around. Thanks for the game finicius!
My preferred line in the English.
This is a little passive for my tastes.

Black's pawn on d6 makes me think he's intending ...e5 or ...c5 which could leave the d-pawn weakened and make it more difficult to advance to give Black's DSB space to maneuver. With that in mind I choose a standard developing move that continues to bear down on d5.
This is a bit mysterious to me. It seems to indicate ...b5 but that doesn't actually seem to be a serious threat.
I don't want to let Black play ...d5 in the event he wins my c-pawn. His position is a little cramped; I want to keep it that way.
Black locks my king-pawn in place but now his d-pawn is backward and weak.
I want to get ready to play d4 without blocking in my Bishop any more than necessary.
Threatening c4.
Reinforcing c4. Another option would have been 7. e3 but I didn't want to tie the d-pawn to defense.
Black begins to lock d4 in return. d5 is now terrifically weak.

? I'm about to lose my chance to play d4 but I'm not pressed for time on castling. I should have played 8.d4 here with the chance to advance to d5 if necessary and preventing ...Nc6 for the time being (8.d4 Nc6 9.d5 wins a piece).
Now it is too late for d4.
This starts the dominoes falling: the center is about to become very tough to navigate.
Moving up to a solid post on d5 expecting to open some space for my Bishop while preventing Black from advancing his doubled d-pawn and trading it off.
Preparing to castle and staving off a check from a White Rook.
Not so much intended to pin the Bishop as to get the Queen moving towards a more active location.
Threatening the Be7 though mostly as a formality to ensure he doesn't play anything surprising while I get a presence on the e-file.
Logical.
I get the Queen out of the way of Black's Rook and begin to put a little pressure on d4 and h7.
It's not like this Bishop has many prospects on e7...
This is a bit of a futile effort to assault the pawn chain but I feel obliged to try. Black has a Knight against my Bishops which could be a losing proposition for me if the board locks up much more.
?! Black pulls my Rook away from the queenside at the cost of control of the open e-file.
Setting up ...Re8.
The pawn chain stands and is now almost unassailable from either side.
There's nothing left to do on a3 but I want to allow myself the option of playing Rb1 if necessary.
Drawing the BQ away from her defense of f5. I want to get behind that pawn chain somehow.
If we're going to make this trade I want to do it on my terms while getting my Bishop into a better position.
Black finally lets his DSB out.
With the Black Bishop locked on the kingside I think I can win the a-pawn.
Setting up Bc1-d2.
Blocking my Bishop momentarily.
?? Black overlooks my Bishop entirely.
?? Playing too quickly I completely miss the free Knight that Black just tried to give me.
It was a one-time offer.
I want to get ready to quickly repel any more intrusions on the kingside while I work on the a-pawn.
Black begins a long march to assault my pawn at d3.
? This pawn is lost whatever Black chooses to do with it. There are better things he could do with his time like try to get his Bishop into play with ...f6 and ...g5.
This is all it takes to keep d3 safe.
Preparing for ...g5 in an attempt to free Black's miserable Bishop.
For now the g-pawn is pinned to the Bishop it was trying to free so I take the chance to lock the kingside down further as I get ready to march or rather crawl to victory on the opposite flank.
I can trap the Knight if it decides to stick around. Otherwise I can drive it off and queen the a-pawn with ease.
The valiant Knight chooses death.
38...Nb8 39. Bc7 is no better. The text line at least breaks up the pawns on Black's terms.
Black's DSB has done next to nothing all game and now its position is even more hopeless than ever.
This is the only spot it might still see use.
d4 is indefensible.
I start to end-around all the debris on the board to get into position to force a pawn through.
Black is just marking time.
This is the beginning of the end as I slowly drive the BK away.
It's about here that I realize that I might not need to promote--I can finagle a KBB mate right here in this tiny corner as long as I don't screw up too badly--the timer is running out fast.
I can't let the BK out of this corner or the mate's off.
Black is (as he has been) out of options.
The King is stuck the Bishop is helpless and pawns are coming.
? This is needless; correct is 61. Kb6 hxg4 62. d7+ Kb8 63. Bd6#
? Again just wasting time trying to prevent Black from pushing his pawns when there's a mate in three sitting right there.
Finally I get around to it.

And so this tortuous tale of positional pandemonium comes to an end. This was certainly one of the longest (number-of-moves-wise) blitz games I've played on Gameknot and while not exactly clean it was certainly fun to play and interesting to analyze. Thanks again to finicius for this game! Comments on the analysis or on the game itself are much appreciated (and if you leave a low rating please tell me what I can improve!). Thanks for reading; hope you enjoyed it!

I've been playing the controversial Latvian Gambit recently and while it's not the most advisable opening for blitz due to the opening's very sharp nature (it's somewhat more popular in long-form games where Black is less likely to misstep and lose in the first dozen moves or so) it has the advantage of likely getting White off-book very quickly (of course at high levels everyone is prepared for this opening) and Black can find a lot of tricky resources. Inadvisable or no it certainly leads to fun games! This game opens with an uncommon line and features several sacrifices (relatively-sound and otherwise) and a minor-piece checkmate. Enjoy!
?! This is the key move of the Latvian Gambit. Black gives up a pawn in exchange for rapid development and lots of attacking potential.

The more common line is 3. Nxe5 Qf6. In the text White is unlikely to be able to protect a pawn on f5 and he gives up his claim to the center. By playing this side line that looks more like a reversed King's Gambit White makes me think he's unfamiliar with the opening. Main lines in the King's Gambit don't really apply very well to the Latvian.

The standard line here is actually 3...e4 4. Ne5 Nf6 5. Be2 d6 6. Bh5+ Ke7 followed by White retreating his Knight and Black playing ...Bxf5 (note that 7. Nf7 loses material and time after 7...Qe1) but I chose a more conservative approach here given that there's time pressure to consider.
? White defends his wayward pawn on f5 at the cost of blocking the d-pawn and crippling his development. I think it's probably better to let the f-pawn go.
Threatening ...e4 forking Knight and Bishop.
White puts off dealing with ...e4 directly since for now he can counter with Re1.
I continue my development. White's already gotten away into his castle so I need to step it up.
This is the easiest way to let the DSB out at this point but it's not destined to get much action pointed straight at a well-defended e5 pawn.
White's just told me with his last move that his Bishop isn't leaving d3 anytime soon so I might as well develop my own LSB.
Threatening ...e4.
Defending e4.

?! This wasn't particularly well thought-out. I probably should have played 7...d5 to allow more options for my DSB. This does renew the threat of ...e4 though which wouldn't actually be possible if the White Rook could still pin it to the BK.
White chooses to pull his Bishop back to give himself some more space on d3.

I finally get the f5 pawn back. Now I'm in a position I'm not used to--normally this opening leaves me significantly behind in material trying to make the most of my advanced development. Here I still have a slight spatial edge but materially we are even.

I don't think this move accomplishes much right now. If White were planning to play c4 he should get the Knight out of the way first and since the only decent place to put that Knight at the moment is b5 I don't see a reason to deny it the Bishop's support prematurely. This move adds a little defense to e4 but otherwise I don't see any reason for it.
In retrospect I wish I had castled queenside. White isn't at all set up for a pawn storm on that flank and this position ends up leaving me a bit more exposed than I would like.
White gets his Rook onto the critical e-file but as yet it can exert no influence with the stymied Bishop blocking its path.

!? At this point I feel like I'm ahead enough in development and open space that I can break the position open and begin an attack. This move frees White's Bishop but I'm feeling like my King is reasonably safe.
White sees an attack coming so he immediately begins trading down.
My development is now complete and my Rooks both occupy powerful open/half-open files.
White's Bishop now has plenty of opportunities for play allowing it to open up an attack by the Rook to win e4.
?! I want to eliminate White's most active piece but it will cost me the exchange. I haven't looked ahead very much so I'm basically just betting that I can get compensation for the Rook.
Forced.
Forced again.
I'm down the exchange but my pieces are a little more active. I'll have to make very good use of my mobility to force White to make more threats than White can respond to.
? White wants to take down my isolated e-pawn but he could do it with pieces. This move weakens his kingside defenses needlessly and gives me an obvious way to press the attack.
19...e3 is probably also playable here but I just didn't see myself getting the pawn all the way through with so much material on the board.
Forking the f and c pawns (I'd prefer to take c2 with the Knight over the Bishop since that would equalize the material) and bringing this Knight up closer to the real action.
This is the only decent move for this Rook as at b1 or d1 I just play 21...Bxc2 and the Rook has to move again anyway.
Threatening the White Rook while opening the path to his King. My Bishops are so much more active than White's are and it's starting to show.
Skewering the Knight and LSB. It's worth noting that White's Knight (and therefore also his DSB) are completely locked down by the threat of ...Be4.
I respond to White's threat and neatly trap the White King.

White cannot let my Bishop off the b1-h7 diagonal or I will be able to move ...Bh3 and White's position becomes very dire. This move by White wins the offending Bishop anyway eliminating my pair and with it my best shot at equalization or victory...
...Unless of course I throw my Rook at the problem. Now all of White's pieces will be locked into a valiant defense of their beleaguered King.

In the game I briefly considered 24...Bh3 (threatening ...Bg2#) and discarded the idea because White has too many defenders for g2. The continuation looks like 24...Bh3 25. Rg1 Ng4 (threatening mate on f2) 26. Rc2 and Black can win back both Rooks but I don't see a clear mate and White is suddenly free to act on the queenside.
White intends to keep his Rook alive as long as possible while adding some muscle to the e4 mating square.
Threatening ...Bg4 and ...Bf3#.
This Rook is about the only piece White can move freely so he goes after my undefended DSB.
I can't quite force the mate after 26...Bh3 27. Rxc5 Ng4 28. Rc2 so I pin White's Knight to avoid letting it into the action (since it's otherwise free now that a Rook is covering e4).

?? With this seemingly-reasonable move White thinks to defend e4 g2 and b2 in one fell swoop but it loses him a huge exchange at the very least. Better was to give back the material with 27. Rxf5 Nxf5 28. Ba3.

! The only way to stop mate at f3 now is 28. Rf1 Bxe2 29. Nxe2 Bxb2 and Black is two pawns a Knight and a Bishop above White's Rook with an easy win in sight. If White doesn't take the Bishop on move 29 and instead plays anything else Black plays 29...Bf3+ 30. Rxf3 Nxf3 and wins handily.
Simply put this move doesn't stop the mate threat. Perhaps White thinks to distract me with check on f6 and the discovered attack on my Bishop but none of that matters.

That's that! The difference in power all game long between Black's active Bishops and White's passive ones is astonishing. This game was great fun to play so many thanks to krishnas83 for that. Comments on the analysis or on the game itself are greatly appreciated (and if you leave a poor rating please comment to tell me what I can improve!). Thanks for reading!
The King's Pawn Opening.
The "cornerstone" of the Sicilian Defense.  However this defense is not going continue and there are several lines that easy 19 wants me to play.  This is going to lead to the Queen Sacrifice.

After this sac you might think that the game is won but "it is not so easy" as Mr. Stockel would say.  That fact is important to remember inside and outside of chess.  In most cases this type of Queen Sacrifice wins the game.  However that is not going to happen here and it will be explained later in the game.
!! At this point he decides to place me in check and it is very serious because it is no longer possible for me to castle.  Therefore my king will be exposed in the worst way.
This move is forced because it is my only option.  After this things will get very interesting and I will explain this concept momentarily.

In this position what am I going to do?  Well there are only three choices and they are: 8...Ke8 8...Kc7 or 8...Kd7.  Either way he can win a free piece with 9.Bxg4 but I am worried about something worse.  What is it?  That will be answered shortly with a shocking surprise.

I was worried that he was going to fork my rook and queen with 9.Nf7.  If he did this I would be forced to retreat my queen.  Then 10.Nxh8 winning the rook so I played this move because I thought that it would prevent the fork.  However I overlooked his LSB so he could have played 9.Nf7.  Consequently 9...Kxf7 would be illegal due to his bishop.  At this point I know that I am loosing because my king is completely exposed and there is nothing that I can do about it as I cannot castle.  As a result he will continue to check me with Bf7+ followed by Be6+.  In the meantime I will keep playing ...Kd7 followed by ...Kd8 because I spot an advantage.  What is the advantage?  If this continues I will be able to trick him into a 3-fold repetition.  BTW this trick was planned when 8.Bxf7+ was played.  On the other hand I did not think that he was going to allow this until he played 11.Bf7+.  That is because I have tried to trick Jack Stockel into a 3 fold repetition when: I was loosing he was trying to mate me and he was continuing to place me in check.

Mr. Stockel would say "Don't give up right away" and "If you know that you cannot win try to get a draw".  Something similar happened in my game against paulr1212 because I made a lot of blunders and some of them were serious.  For that reason I was in a loosing position and had almost lost but I was also able to trick him into a 3 fold repetition.  After this game was finished I learned something from easy19.  What was it?  Fred told me that he has played this variation many times and almost always wins with this queen sac so I was lucky that he was not paying attention to this attempted trick.  On a normal basis he would have captured the knight with 9.Bxg4 instead of playing 9.Bf7+.  If he took my knight or rook the game would have been lost.

that is Levenfish attack  in dragon variation  the idea is to forward whites pawn to e5 and get  strong space and center advantage . black must be careful now if .6....Bg7?.7.e5-Nd7.8.e6 with big advantage. if 7....Ng4 black in lost position after 8.Bg4+Bd7.9. Qxg4 or 8....Nc6.9.Nxc6-bxc.10.Bxc6+ and last one .7....Kf8.9.h3 and the black knight is traped 9....dxe5 will lose quicker after .10. Ne6+Bxe6.11.Qxd8+
10....Be7 is the correct move  maybe black wishes to not showing white where the black bishop will move  but he's must recole that it  has aweak pawn on d6.
good move  centre-ling the queen on strong position d4 and there is no Pisces that get her away without make more weaknesses  in blacks positions
maybe  .16.Bf1 is batter ?
good move  white attacking the weak pawn d6 and controls the center butt  the white king stays in the center with out castling and it could be big problem for whites

18. Qd4 was stronger move attacking the queen on e3 the pawn on a7 and d6. its not good for black 18....Qxd4.19.Bxa6+Kb8.19.Rxd4.or 18....Qe6.19. Qxa7 with big advantage  after 19....Re81!.20.Qxe3-Rxe3.21.Rxd6 white stays with pawn advantage and good position .
Big mistake for white it seems that black just lost abishop on a3 but the weak king on the center can pay abig price .
now black is mistake the correct move was 19.....Kb8!! that  gives black  awinnig position after 20. Rxa6-Nc5.21.Ra3-Rd2 .

and ad raw was agreed because of 22.....Qc1-e3+ . another option was 22. Qxf7+Rd7.23.Qc4-Nxa6.Qxa6+ = that's why 19.....Kb8 was better move . The English opening.
Black chooses a reversed-Sicilian which suits me fine and frequently (in my experience) leads to very sharp play--perfect for blitz chess.
My preferred continuation. 2. Nc3 is perfectly playable here as well.
This move has the potential to transition many different ways. Most importantly to me it indicates that Black plans to seriously contest control of d5.
Other popular moves here are 3. b3 3. d4 3. Nf3 and 3. Bg2. I chose the text move to show a confrontational stance--I'm not giving Black d5 without a fight.
Planning to fianchetto the Bishop to compete with me along the a8-h1 diagonal. I haven't seen any theory supporting this move but I don't necessarily dislike it.
We both continue our development and I begin to prepare for an eventual d4.
This is about the only way to shore up e5 so Black's ...d5 push will have to wait.
I feel like e5 is weak so I get ready to pressure it and support my coming advance to d4.
Black needs to catch up in development so this is logical. 6...Nd7 would be fine as well I think.
Preparing to castle. This is the best spot for that Bishop at the moment since Black's d-pawn can't get out of the way just yet.
I have a slight edge in development and initiative so I want to break the position open before he can catch up.
This is a solid move as ...d5 is coming and that advanced pawn will be well defended.
Threatening e4 mostly as a formality.
White cannot remove this defender efficiently.
I attack the pawn chain head-on planning 10...exf3 11. exf3 followed by O-O and f4.

! Lending the Bishop's support to e4 and increasing the tension in the center. He wants to complicate the situation so I'll make a misstep--the same general idea that I favor in blitz games. Things are about to get really hairy; one wrong move on either side could spell disaster.

Given the complicated nature of the position I feel it's wise to get my King out of the way. I'm also starting to think about sacrificing my Knight on f7 if Black doesn't castle soon in order to attract the Black King into the path of my Rook.
Black tries to kick my Knight back to a dismal post at h3 giving him a clear advantage in the center and the initiative.
I think I can get compensation for the Knight. I have a slight developmental advantage and 12...Kxf7 13. fxe4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Rf8 15. d5 Kg8 looks promising.
Pretty much forced.
As planned pinning Black's Knight.
?! This surprised me a little. Obviously Black wants to avoid letting me play 14. e5 and 13...Kg8 would trap his Rook but g6 feels like a very exposed path to h7.
I decide to stuff Black's dangerous LSB while claiming a third pawn in exchange for my Knight and opening up the b1-h7 diagonal for my Queen and/or Bishop.
? This feels out-of-place and Black can't afford the tempo. He needed to play 14...Kh7 here because now he's about to lose his chance.
I force Black's King back into the pin and free my a1 Rook.
Black pulls back (not that he had much choice) and is now only a move away from relative safety on g8.
I want to keep Black tangled and keep the pressure on; the loss of my d-pawn is worth keeping the King out of his safehouse.
Black accepts the proffered pawn threatening to open a line for the dark Bishop to the White King.
! After 17...dxc3 18. Bxc3 the Black King must retreat to e8 (allowing Qxg7 and a strong position) to avoid my pawn advancing to e5 and winning a piece.
Black sees it and decides to deny me the powerful center pawns. Now he threatens ...Bc4 and ...e2.
Black can't play 18...e2 to any effect right now so I centralize my Knight and unchain my Bishop bringing up more pieces to renew my attack.
Black needs reinforcements as well and extra support for the f6 Knight doesn't hurt.

At this point I have a feeling Black is about ready to give up on g8 and bring his King back to e8 freeing his Knight against my Queen. There are a lot of pieces between e1 and e8 but only the Bishop defends d6 and e8 seems awfully cramped. Thus this move.

? And there it is. Black needed to get his King someplace a little safer though looking back I actually think this move is Black's biggest misstep for reasons that will become clear soon. For now the White Queen is in danger again and White has a few options to deal with it. Without looking ahead what would you play?
20. Qxg7 or 20. Qg6+ are strong as well but frankly I think this is the flashiest way to go about protecting my wayward Queen (and pressing the assault and setting a trap--remember this is blitz!).

Black under time pressure and grasping for useful moves doesn't see the danger! He has very few better choices here as his position is to put it mildly cramped and the huge number of variations to follow is a serious concern with only a few minutes left on the clock. The BK can escape with his life after 20...Qc7 after which Black may be able to trade down to a livable (but difficult) endgame. 20...Nxe4 loses to 21. Qg6+ Rf7 22. Qxf7# and 20...Nc5 looks promising at first but the situation becomes hopeless after 21. Nd6+ Kd7 22. Qf5+ Kc7 (22...Kxd6 Be5#) 23. Nb5+ Kb8 24. Be5+ Bd6 25. Bxd6+ Qxd6 26. Nxd6.

And there you have it a couple sacrifices resulting in a neat little Knight mate on the BK's home square. This game was great fun to play; I hope you enjoyed it. Comments on the game/annotation are greatly appreciated. Thanks for reading!
A simple Philidor nothing much to see here.
White would rather pressure Black's position than go for the bloodbath in the center of the board.
White is amassing the forces while Black is content to dig in and get ready to attack later.
Black is packing his pieces in.  It looks rather cramped.  Something will happen soon though as White will not get through Black's defense without blasting through Black's center.
We have traded bishop and pawn; Black's center formation looks relatively secure but more development for both sides would be nice.
White still attacking although it will take more than this to get through Black's center.
A bad attack.  White is trying to pin the bishop but evidently has forgotten that the bishop can attack.  A lost piece.
Black now has the upper hand - the king in the corner and unable to move - and who is attacking now?  The tables have turned.
A cheap checkmate attempt which White sees through easily enough.
The kingside is heating up.  Black apparently falling back into defense again.
An opening salvo to open a few things up.
Black eschews the 21...g5 opportunity which would be aggressive defense but would possibly leave the king open to more attack.
A curious move - Ne2 might have been better.
Attacks for both sides White's looking more dangerous despite being a bishop and pawn down.
A bad mistake for Black.  A lost queen certainly not to put Black out of the game but it won't make things easy.
A mistake by White to put Black back in the game.  I see Black as slightly ahead.
Black doesn't have a whole lot of moves yet his king looks reasonably secure.  He will need help to get out of this one though.
Black has turned the tables.  White has a free rook.
White may as well tie up one of Black's rooks and threaten a promotion.
Might as well gobble up a pawn while we're down there.
The forced movement of the king is no longer viable and the pawn has to be dealt with.
A counter to the queen's defense of the promotion square.
White must give up on the pawn.
The pawn to be taken finally.
White trying to put some pressure on Black's remaining pawns but Black is forcing the queen to move. This will be over before long.
This could have been done a move before but it does the same thing. White resigned here his mistakes having been worse than Black's.
First amazing move: d4 instead of usual e4!!
From Black 7th move I thought that he mustn't defense this Pawn!
I think my attack will be strong enough!
Black try to trap my Rook!
An important move: Black King cant scape to King side!
I never think of taking the Black Rook on a8!!
Without hope!
The Van't Kruijs. Not a popular opening at high levels but notable for its transpositional potential and used famously on multiple occasions by Kasparov against the Fritz engine.
More popular are 1...e5 or 1...d5 but I was hoping for 2.c4 b6 and a reversed Nimzovitch-Larsen attack.
With this second unusual move we stray further from the book and the usual transpositions. I think 2.b3 2.c4 or 2.Nf3 are stronger and more straightforward.
I was already planning to fianchetto this bishop; it's an even more obvious choice now with b4 in White's control.

Again I think 2.b3 is cleaner. This is certainly more aggressive but I've already made it clear that I don't intend to seriously contest the b4 square right away. As of this move we are entirely off-book (with one game in Gameknot's World database following this line for another couple of moves).
Releasing the queen's bishop and preparing for an eventual ...c5.
Continuing to develop the queenside aggressively. I think 5.Nf3 or 5.c4 might be more in line with the attack White is preparing here; he could benefit from the assistance of the c-pawn.
I think ...Nc6 or even ...Bg4 would be fine here but I was wary of an early pawn push against my undeveloped queenside. I'll also need to expand eventually so I put the Knight where it can see c5.

Mildly restricting ...c5 for now though I felt at the time like this weakened White's queenside unnecessarily. I'm going to get c5 eventually; I think a simple developing move might have been stronger for White.
I take a moment to collect myself in case all those pawns start pouring down the board. I'm also getting my King out of the way for when the position inevitably opens up.
White starts mobilizing his kingside.

At the time I was concerned about 7...c5 8.d5 e6 9.e4 and my resulting backwards pawn at d6 but I don't think it looks so bad now. 7...b6 followed by ...Bb7 before playing ...c5 would probably do better; this e6 pawn proves to haunt my position for a long time to come.

I'm not sure of the purpose behind this move. White may be aiming for a Knight on e4 or c4 but either post is easily assailable and exchanging one of his knights for my expendable one on f6 doesn't seem productive.
With the White Queen momentarily out of the picture this is a good time to get off my back three ranks.

The computer labels this an inaccuracy and gives the continuation 9...Nd5 10. Ndb1 dxc5 11. b5 a6 12. Ra2 Nc7 13. bxa6 Nxa6 which certainly looks good for Black with a significant developmental lead and good prospects against White's cramped position. The computer recommends 9.Be2 instead...
But I don't see the discovered pin on the Knight and simply recapture.
Risky but aggressive and my Queenside is still looking pretty unprepared for a real attack. The computer thinks 10.Nc4 is better here (to protect against ...Nd5).

The computer is still obsessed with ...Nd5 but I'm not feeling that aggressive at this point in the game. I'm trying to clamp down on White's advanced position and get my Bishop into the action but...

...There goes my Bishop's only good square and it's going to take some work to get him into play. This move also puts some pressure on my Knight on f6 threatening to open up a powerful discovered attack down the long diagonal.
Blocking the attack down the h1-a8 diagonal and preparing for ...Bb7. I open up my own pin first to keep White's Knight from trying anything tricky.

The computer lists this as an inaccuracy and I agree. While it doesn't lose material this Knight push nets me a tempo after ...f5 which I can then use to play ...Bb7. I think the intention was to aim at d6 while defending the Knight on c3 but that piece is in no real danger (12.O-O-O Bxc3 13.Bxc3 Nxc3 14.Qxa8 Nxd1 15.Kxd1 leaves White in fine position).
Picking up a little space and gaining a tempo to play ...Bb7 after the Knight retreats.
?? This is simply an oversight. White doesn't have enough to threaten anything significant and hangs a piece.
I really wanted to keep my Bishop around and I was afraid of hanging my Rook if I got greedy and started taking more Knights right away. 14...exd5 is definitely better here.

?? This is not the correct Knight to give me. White would get the pawn back anyway but at least after 15.Nd2 Ne5 (not 15...exd4? 16.Qxd4+ Kh8 17.Qxa8) 16.Ne7+ Qxe7 17.Qxa8 Qc7 18.f4 Bd7 19.Qxf8+ Kxf8 20.fxe5 Qxe5 White has decent if maybe not enough compensation.
The material is nice but now I have to keep an eye on my isolated undefended e6 pawn.
The critical difference between this move and the line mentioned above: White takes back without check. But now he threatens e6 and my Rook at a8 so how am I to defend both?
! Driving the King into the open.
? 17.Kd1 looks ugly at first glance because of 17...Nd6+ but after 18.Qd3 there really isn't as much to worry about and White's King is a little safer than he is on e2.
This Knight finally gets into the fight unleashing the Black Queen and defending the weak e6 pawn in the process. I've dealt with both of the White Queen's threats for now.
The only move. If 18.Qxa8?? 18...Qd2#.

?? My thought process here was that after 18...Bb7 19.Qxb7 Ng4 20.Kd1 Nxf2 and I get the rook then the bishop and win easily. What I failed to notice is that the Knight doesn't actually check White's King from g4 so the King has no reason to move and my poor patient Bishop dies for no good reason. 18...c4 would have been a much better choice.

Steadfastly sticking to my plan even though I realize at this point that I've given back a large portion of my advantage. I still threaten f2 and White's development is too far behind to defend it efficiently.
Better than letting me take f2 with check.

It's worth noting that I could still play ...c4 in here pretty much any time but I want to consolidate my pieces first. White's King can't take my Knight here without exposing himself to a deadly attack from my Queen Bishop and Rook.
Black brings the Queen back to someplace useful and threatens to take the Knight and get his other pieces off the back rank.

Trying to get out of the way of the light-square Bishop so White can get his last two pieces into play. Getting the King off the e file also threatens Qxe6+ without having to worry about a game-ending pin.
Getting out of the way of Qxe6+ and inviting White to take the pawn confident that giving my rook the e file would be well worth the material.
White continues to work to consolidate his position not taking the bait on e6.
So I continue to do my best to keep the Rook from escaping its corner. The King has to retreat and the Rook stays out of play for at least another two turns.

I'm comfortable enough with White's awkward position that I can spare the tempo to defend the e-pawn. With this move I transition from my earlier defensive posture into all-out prophylaxis mode; my goal now is to slowly tighten the noose until White is forced to give up something decisive. The computer suggests Nd6 instead which opens up the position a bit and is certainly playable.

?! Freeing the Rook and reinforcing the queenside momentarily but hanging a pawn in the process. I like 25.g3 or 25.f4 here instead with an eye toward hiking the King over to c1 or b1 and freeing the h-Rook.
The Knight returns to this menacing outpost forking g2 and c4. My Knight and Bishop are unassailable right now and White would dearly love to be rid of them.

I think 26.g3 is better here. There's no reason to overadvance the g-pawn; it makes f3 and f4 unnecessarily weak and doesn't accomplish anything that 26.g3 wouldn't. There are a few other options that provide a bit of counterplay for White but I can't see anything better than g3.

Picking up the free pawn. I considered leaving the Knight on e3 because it's just so strong there or trying 26...Ng2+ and trying to drive the White King into a nasty discovered check or fork but this seemed the most straightforward and doesn't let White's Rook on h1 out.
Threatening the Knight and pinning the Bishop momentarily. White's Knight is now in an ugly spot but at least the Rook on a2 has a path out.
Tossing in a check before I deal with the Knight opening up the d-file and forcing the White King to f2 (if 28.Kf1?? Nd2+ 29.Rxd2 Bxd2 and Black wins easily).
Forced but at least it lets the h1 Rook out at last.
Moving the Knight out of harm's way and blocking White's other Rook from contributing.
I think 29.Nd3 is better here. The Knight doesn't really have any prospects from b3. Alternatively 29.h4 gives White some counterplay.
Piling on the d-file but more importantly getting the Rook out of the Queen's sights and threatening ...Rf4.
Getting out of the pin and away from my Knight and Bishop. Another option is 30.Rc1 which leads one way or another to some favorable exchanges for White.
At last the long-awaited ...c4 appears. After 31.Bxc4 Rf4 32.Qc2 Rxc4 33.Rxb2 Qd5 34.Rbb1 Rf8 35.Qe2 Rxg4+ I'll end up in a very commanding position.

? Not as strong as the line I gave in 30...c4. This move eliminates my position's biggest weakness (the pawn at e6 that's been hounding me all game) wins me the Bishop and trades off White's most powerful piece.

?! The computer lists this as a mistake preferring to take with the Knight. I wanted to keep White's Rook and Knight locked away but now my interlocked R/N/B trio is going to make my life difficult. 32...Nxc4 would maybe have been easier.
Setting up an obnoxious pin on the Bishop threatening Rxb2 or Rxc3.
At this point I come out ahead in even exchanges so after 35.Nd2 Rxg4+ 36.fxg4 Nxc1 37.Ne4 Nxa2 38.Nxd6 the resulting NB vs N game should be a solid fun win for me.
? Not the exchange line I was hoping for but this is a subtle mistake White couldn't afford to make.
Forking the King and Rook.
? The computer labels this a mistake but I think White is already lost at this point.
The pawn is more tempting than the Rook now. White's pieces are locked down pretty effectively and there's blood in the water.
I think Ra1 is a little better at this point to try to entice some trades and ease Black's pressure off.
The beginning of the end. 38.Kg2 leads to mate in four and 38.Kh4 loses a Rook and Knight for my Bishop after 38...Be1+ 39.Rf2 Bxf2+ 40.Rxf2 Rxc1.
But White heads for g2 letting me set up an elegant mate.
39.Kh1 holds out one extra turn.

And that's all there is. I hope you enjoyed it and my thanks to cetst11 for a very good match! (I won't be annotating the other game in this match; I made some bad mistakes and he seized on them immediately crushing me simply and quickly. A quick game but not particularly interesting.) Comments and ratings are much appreciated!

Hi everyone!

This game was part of the Sicilian Pelikan themed MT started by Concordborn.  It was a victory against an opponent with an optimum rating of 1903.  This is a long game spanning 69 moves.  I managed to be a pawn up in a Q & P ending and to shepherd my extra pawn to Glendadom.  Meanwhile Henry had to run the gauntlet from the Wicked Witch of the West.  He did this by using an enemy pawn as a Human Shield.  After that his two wives then covered him aaaah!  Once the checks ran out my opponent waved the white flag.  Here is how it happened folks - firstly here is the Gameknot Analysis.   http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=17526707&rnd=0.10930306846589815
4. Nxd4 - the standard pawn trade.
7. Bg5 - pin.  This threatens BxN forcing PxB because if QxB?? then Nc7+.
8....... b5 - threatening b4 forking the two knights.
10. .... Bxf6 - B for N trade.
14. Rxa4 - pawn trade.  This pawn trade gives black a weak pawn on a6.  Such a trade happened in my game against Concordborn called Breakthrough which I went on to win.
17. ...... Qxf6 - N for B trade.
21. ...... Bxd5 - another set of minor pieces plus a pawn have been traded.  Will black's bishop be better than my knight?  We shall see.

24. 0-0 - I remember castling late in the Concordborn game in which Coach Ion said that in this variation white was too busy to castle.  It is certainly time to get a rook into play particularly with a BR controlling the d column.
26. Rxg4 - the minor pieces have been traded off and I now have pressure on the g column.
28. Re1 - and now the e5 pawn comes under the hammer.
29. Rge4 - pile on.
31. ..... f6 - black tries to save his pawn but to no avail.
35. Re1 - blocking the check.  Black now backs up his rook and covers his back row.
36. ..... Qxd1+ - now the rooks have been traded off we have a Q and P ending but with me a pawn up I will win this but boy I am gonna be in for the long haul.
40. Qd4 - and even in this endgame Glenda is put to do a lot of defending - poor put upon lady!
41. c4 - it will be this pawn that will crown however.  Only another 4 squares to go but they will be tortuous steps.
42. c5 - make that 3.
44. c6 - only 2 to go.
46. Kf2 - Henry is eyeing up the top of the board.  He intends to seek shelter there against any checks from the Wicked Witch.
50. c7 - a series of queen checks enables my pawn to be just one square from Glendadom.  But now Henry must run the gauntlet from the Wicked Witch of the West.
54. Kg3 - Henry hatches his escape plan.
57. Kd3 - Henry makes towards his queenside footman but will this be shelter enough?
60. Kb3 - whew - at last Henry has found some refuge as the Witch has no checking lines available.  Any non checking move will allow my c7 pawn to crown.
61. c8/Q - Voila!

62. Kc2 - Henry must run the gauntlet yet again.  At least with two queens on the board it will be easier to cover Henry as more squares will be controlled by both these ladies.  I just hope I can engineer a cross-check which will force off the Witch.
64. Kc4 - with both queens defending each other Henry has no fear of running into a skewer.

66. Ka6! - Henry was really tempted to gobble up that nice tasty juicy p(r)awn on a5.  But he restrains himself from this because he realises that he can use this pawn as a human shield to shelter behind.  Black cannot now check Henry from the front so he must now find another way.
68. Qb6 - After being on this square for many moves Glenda is finally able to cover her other half.

69. Qcb7 - and so does her clone Henry is sooo lucky having those two ladies to snuggle up to.  My opponent acknowledges that Henry is now safe and all I have to do is to plonk a queen on the b1 to a7 diagonal when the Witch moves off her second rank and I will either force an exchange of queens or if black dodges this exchange he can cop Old Matey.  This acknowledgement comes in the form of the white flag.  This puts me back to my optimum rating of 1883 just 17 points short of 1900.  Be really lurvely to get there.  But for now that's all folks bye for now - Joanne

Is it just me or is my opponent not understanding the purpose of this opening. White is trying to develop the Queenside first by playing this move.
I want to try for 3...d5.
3...d5 is not so great but it's playable along with 3...Bc5.
Black is slightly better but might have to deal with a troublesome e-pawn.
Well I think White had better moves which include 5.Bb2.
My goal is to help my Knight develop

La apertura Catalana que fue empleada por primera vez en Barcelona. De ahí su nombre.
Una movida arriesgada que muestra ya el espíritu combativo de Gurevich. Lo principal es 7..a6.

No tenía ningún problema en jugar una partida tranquila y posicional. Era la segunda ronda del día- el torneo se jugaba con doble ronda diaria- y no disponía de las energías suficientes para jugar una partida complicada llena de combinaciones.
Comenzando con una danza de caballos que se extenderá hasta el fin de la partida.

En este tipo de finales los caballos suelen ser más fuertes que los alfiles. A pesar de haber peones en ambos flancos los negros del flanco de dama están muy avanzados y fijados y pronto se volverán débiles.
Si 30...Cxc6 entonces 31.Cxf6 jaque doble ganando una pieza luego de Rg7 32.Cxd7.
Aunque aún es preciso trabajar el blanco goza de una clara ventaja.
Sin muchas esperanzas Gurevich abandonó luego de realizar su movimiento.

White opens with a kingside attack. Black responds by accepting and thus up a pawn. My common thinking here is that advancing the e and f pawns is risky because if white makes a mistake the king is vulnerable. If black makes a mistake black is down a pawn or maybe a piece.
Both sides prepare for further king side activity.
White moves to control the center and attack the f4 pawn.
Black moves to protect the f4 pawn and threaten moving to g3.
Black and white get more pieces ready to roll.
With two pieces attacking the f4 pawn and only one defending white moves to restore parity.
White moves the queen out so the king can castle.

Castling lines up rook with queen and lets the rook provide mutual protection. With white's queen and rook lined up white can advance the center pawns and push black back. White can also push the pawns to threaten pieces in order to get material superiority.
Queen moves where it is not in the line of fire if the d6 pawn is under attack. This also lets the queen move out the white diagonal if/when the knight moves off c6.
Line up rook so black can push pawn to threaten the white bishop.
White provides a safe square for the bishop.
The bishop on f6 and knight on f3 can threaten the d4 pawn - but that's not safe if white's knight is still around to protect it.
White gives the pawn some more protection.
Now black can threaten the e4 pawn.

This does not seem wise. There are 3 white pieces protecting the e pawn but 5 black pieces attacking it. By exchanging several pieces on e5 black can move its forces out into the open where they have more mobility.
The exchange begins.
The exchange ends with four captures and the center columns cleared of pawns.

Threaten white queen to get it move away. Another purpose of this move is so black can move the pawn a step further and block white's bishop on a2. This move has a third purpose which will become evident later.
Bishop blocked. White could advance the b2 pawn to unblock the bishop but this will do for now.

White moves another piece to attack the beleaguered knight. The knight seems in danger with 3 attackers and only 2 defenders. This is where the real fun begins as the purpose of previous moves becomes obvious.

Knight forks king and rook! The black queen is exposed to attack but that doesn't matter since white's king is under attack and the black queen is free to move! This was the true purpose of advancing the pawn to c4 - to give the knight a perch from where it can check the king. If Kb1 then Nxe1 followed by Rxe1 Qxe1 with white down two rooks. The same happens if Kc2 or Kd2.
The only way for white to avoid losing two rooks with nothing in return is to sacrifice a queen!

Black doesn't accept white's sacrifice just yet. Instead black sacrifices his own queen instead! If white moves the king to c2 now black picks off the other rook as a prize. If Qd2 blocks then a series of exchanges on e1 leaves black ahead with two rooks against two bishops. (Qxe1 followed by Rxe1 and Bxe1 and Kxe1 and Rd8+.) No move leads to a good outcome for white.

White accepts the queen sacrifice and appears to have material superiority. (Actually white does not have effective material superiority since the white queen is ready to be taken and both bishops are too far from the action to influence events.)
Black follows by taking white's other rook. The king is in check again.
King moves to temporary safety.
Black finally accepts white's sacrificed queen and just in time to put king in check yet again.

If the king moved to b3 instead then black would counter with Bd1+ king moves to b4 followed by Re4+ which forces white to lose the dark square bishop. If the king moved to d2 to block the pawn on d3 then white would move Rd1+ Ke3 Re8+ followed soon by mate. White's best option here was probably to avenge the queen by taking the pawn.
Moving the rook to d8 pushes the king back into a corner.
King moves to temporary safety.
The bishop sets the king up for a discovered check.

King only has 2 options left. One leads to checkmate in 1 move. The other leads to checkmate in a few more moves. (Kb1 Ba4+ then Bc1 to block followed by Rd8d1 to line up the rooks for mate. White would only have a few delaying tactics after that.)
The game ends with a discovered checkmate!

This is where Bobby Fisher would say "Best by Test".  For a long time I have been wondering what "Best by Test" meant.  Liam1260 and expert inadowman gave a very good opinion of that statement.  Bobby Fisher tested this opening and determined that it is best and that is what he means when he says "Best by Test".  According to Jack Stockel 1.e4 is still the strongest opening and that is why it is also the most common.  However he has also told me that other openings are quite playable as long as they are studied by masters and grandmasters.

This was Bobby Fisher's favorite defense.  He opened with the Sicilian defense against a Russian player. I do not know what his name was but he was also a grandmaster.  This is how Bobby Fisher defeated that player in a long game.  For that reason Bobby Fisher would also say "Best by Test" for this opening.
He probably wanted to respond with the Open Sicilian but it is a little early for this move.  If wanted the Open Variation he should have played 2.Nf3 followed by 3.d4.
However I am going to continue with my defense.

? This violates General Opening Principles because he brought his queen out too early.  However I am not going to drive it away.  As I had mentioned in my last annotation it can be harmful if you become obsessed with chasing pieces.  For that reason I am going to continue with my defense.  In addition he has left his d4 pawn unprotected.  Therefore I am going to win a free pawn after 3...cxd4.
? I don't know why he played this.
I made this move for development.  However it is not the proper continuation of the Siclian Defense.  Therefore 4...a6 would have been best.

?! Why did he attack my knight?  He probably did this to use a "Scare Tactic".  However that is not going to overwhelm me because my knight is not pinned.  Therefore he is not going to accomplish anything if he wants to make me nervous.

?! In the meantime I decide to attack his queen but what is my goal?  Well I am attacking with two pieces.  Therefore I will win a free pawn with my knight if he does not retreat carefully.  BTW I am not attempting tempo but I am trying to win free material.  However this does not guarantee victory and it is a waste of time.  That will be explained shortly.
!! He retreats wisely.  In fact this was his best move and I will explain it shortly.

?? On a normal basis I would this two exclamation points because I originally thought that he was threatening my rook.  However I would still be able to protect it with this move if Qxb7 was played.  On the other hand this turns out to be a major blunder because he is going to place me in a very serious check after 7.Bxf7+.  Therefore I am going to loose my chance to castle so my king will remain exposed throughout the entire.  In the past I have lost several chess games from this type of mistake.  That is why 6...e6 would have been my best move.
!! At this point he takes advantage by deciding to place me in another serious check.  Why is this serious?  It is because he has won another free pawn due to this check.

This is forced.  I originally thought that I could protect with my king but that would be illegal.  Therefore this is my only move.  Right now things are looking very bad for black because he will win a free rook after 9.Qxa8.  As a result I will 6 points behind instead of a point ahead.

!! Before he does any more damage I decide to place him in check.  This might look like a nuisance and a waste of time but it is quite.  What is the significance of this move?  That will be answered shortly.
This gets him out of check but I am now going to win his DSB after 10...Qxg5 due to my last move.

It might look serious because 11...Kd8 will be forced but this is a nuisance check because I am protected by my knights and LSB.  On a normal basis you would think that the game is almost lost for black.  However white has made a serious game that will cost him the game.  That will be explained momentarily.

?? He played this to win a free piece but "almost anything is better than this move" as chesskingdom64 would say.  In fact "this looses immediately" as Mr. Stockel would say.  It turns out to be a deflective sacrifice because I now have an inevitable mating move.  Therefore I will mate him in one with 12...Qc1#.  That is btw why it is called Back Rank Mate.  Afterall I am going to mate him on the back rank.

In the past chesskingdom64 has said that "What you do in the opening will affect you in the midgame; what you do in the midgame will affect you in the endgame; what you do in the endgame will the final results".  Jack Stockel strongly agrees with this assessment.  He has said that it is very hard to catchup if your opening is weak.  However there are also times where you can play and/or end well despite a weak opening.  That was shown in this game.  IM i-have-arrived emphasized that in my thread about opening games.  Having said that I would like to thank i-have-arrived for making this point.  By doing this he has helped to make this annotation possible.
